The new CacheBuilder code is great, but not every use of computing maps is for caching.  We use it often for abstracting the creation of objects.  As a concrete example, consider some code that writes events to files based on a partition.

Using a compute map:

```
outputFiles.get(partition).write(event);
```

Without a compute map:

```
OutputFile file = outputFiles.get(partition);
if (file == null) {
    OutputFile file = new OutputFile(partition);
    outputFiles.put(partition, file);
}
file.write(event);
```

The latter code is much harder to understand and is also incorrect, because it lacks synchronization.  It's not possible to add the same fine-grained synchronization that compute maps provide without substantially restructuring and complicating the code.

I don't want to use a Cache here because it's certainly not a cache and iterating over the entries requires calling asMap (when, from my perspective, it already should be a map).

